ite web |url= http://www.chaharmahalmet.ir/stat/archive/iran/alb/KARAJ/32.asp |title= No. of days with snow or sleet in Karaj by Month 1985\u20132010 |publisher= Iran Meteorological Organization |accessdate= April 7, 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150414131810/http://www.chaharmahalmet.ir/stat/archive/iran/alb/KARAJ/32.asp |archive-date= April 14, 2015 |url-status= dead |df= mdy-all }}</ref> (sunshine)<ref name=sunshine>\n*{{cite web |url= http://www.chaharmahalmet.ir/stat/archive/iran/alb/KARAJ/42.asp |title= Monthly total sunshine hours in Karaj by Month 1985\u20132010 |publisher= Iran Meteorological Organization |accessdate= April 7, 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150414141402/http://www.chaharmahalmet.ir/stat/archive/iran/alb/KARAJ/42.asp |archive-date= April 14, 2015 |url-status= dead |df= mdy-all }}</ref>\n}}\n\n[[Amir Kabir Dam]] and some other small lakes are based in Karaj. The city is a starting point for a drive along road forced north through the [[Alborz]] mountain to the [[Caspian Sea]].<ref>''[https://books.google.com/books?id=PNYLJakw1SQC&pg=PA117 Iran. Ediz. Inglese]'' by Andrew Burke, Mark Elliott, and Kamin Mohammadi, 2004</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nIran-Karaj montains.jpg|Karaj Valley\nKaraj, winter.jpg|Karaj in winter \nKaraj dam.jpg|[[Karaj Dam]]\nAmirKabirDam02.jpg|Another view of the Karaj Dam\nMan in green.jpg|[[Ajin Dojin|\u0100jin Dojin]]\n</gallery>\n\n== Demographics ==\n{{bar box\n| title=Ethnic groups of Karaj (Pars advanced research scholars)<ref>{{cite web|title=Pars|url=http://farsi.parsprobe.com/|website=Pars|access-date=2016-02-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160217035803/http://farsi.parsprobe.com/|archive-date=2016-02-17|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| titlebar=#ddd\n| left1='''Ethnic groups'''\n| right1='''Percent'''\n| float=right\n| bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Persian people|Persians]] |red|48.3|53%}}\n{{bar percent|[[Iranian Azerbaijanis|Azerbaijanis]]|green|35|30%}}\n{{bar percent|[[Kurds]]|blue|15|7.2%}}\n{{bar percent|[[Gilaks]] and [[Mazanderani people|Mazanders]]|yellow|10.5|5%}}\n{{bar percent|[[Lurs]]|purple|3.5|4.1%}}\n}}\n\nThe majority of the residents of Karaj are [[Persian-speaking people]], with [[Iranian Azerbaijanis|Azerbaijanis]] making up the second major ethno-linguistic group of the city. [[Kurds]], [[Gilaks]], [[Mazanderani people|Mazanders]] and [[Lurs]] include the other ethnicities among the population of Karaj.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Gender segregation population in 2016\n!Male\n!Female\n!Total\n!Ref.\n|-\n|890,824\n|886,570\n|1,759,394\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amar.org.ir/|title=\u062f\u0631\u06af\u0627\u0647 \u0645\u0644\u06cc \u0622\u0645\u0627\u0631|website=www.amar.org.ir|access-date=2019-06-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190906071718/https://www.amar.org.ir/|archive-date=2019-09-06|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Population by age group in 2016 (%)\n!age (0\u201314 years)\n!age (15\u201329 years)\n!age (30\u201364 years)\n!age (65 and more years)\n|-\n|20.3%\n|23.6%\n|50.2%\n|6.0%\n|}\n\n== Transport ==\n{{see also|Transport in Iran}}\n[[File:Golshahr metRo.jpg|thumb|220px|[[Golshahr Metro Station]]|alt=]]\n\n=== Railway ===\nKaraj is connected by railway and highways to Tehran 40&nbsp;km east and [[Qazvin]] 100&nbsp;km northwest, and by commuter rail to [[Tehran Metro|the subway system of Tehran]].\n\nThe city is served by an urban railway organization established on 21 December 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://irtco.ir/en/pages/content.php?id=26|title=Karaj Urban Railway History|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304110146/http://irtco.ir/en/pages/content.php?id=26|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=dead|access-date=2015-05-27}}</ref><ref>[http://www.irangulistan.com/cartes/train/iran-railways-map.jpg Iran Railways Map]</ref> It is also served by the [[Karaj Metro Station]] which was established on 7 March 1999, and is located in the south-eastern Karaj, near [[Freeway 2 (Iran)|Tehran\u2013Qazvin Freeway]]. \n[[File:Karaj Metro map-Planned-geo.png|thumb|300px|right|Karaj Metro operational and under construction lines]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Karaj 6 lines information\n! Line\n! Line Route\n! Length\n! Stations\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#FFFFFF; background-color:#fffa00\" | '''[[Tehran Metro Line 1|{{color|black|1}}]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" |'''\u06af\u0631\u0645\u062f\u0631\u0647 \u2013 \u06af\u0644\u0634\u0647\u0631 \u2013 \u067e\u0627\u06cc\u0627\u0646\u0647 \u0645\u0647\u0631\u0634\u0647\u0631'''\n| 17km (10.5mi)\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | 4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#FFFFFF; background-color:#15ff00\" | '''[[Tehran Metro Line 2|{{color|black|2}}]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" |'''\u06a9\u0645\u0627\u0644\u0634\u0647\u0631 \u2013 \u0686\u0647\u0627\u0631\u0631\u0627\u0647 \u0637\u0627\u0644\u0642\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u2013 \u0645\u06cc\u062f\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0645\u0627\u0645 \u062d\u0633\u06cc\u0646 \u2013 \u0634\u0647\u0631 \u0645\u0644\u0627\u0631\u062f'''\n| 27km (16mi)\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | 23\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#FFFFFF; background-color:#00ffdd\" | '''[[Tehran Metro Line 3|{{color|black|3}}]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" |'''\u0627\u06cc\u0633\u062a\u06af\u0627\u0647 \u06a9\u0631\u062c (\u0645\u06cc\u062f\u0627\u0646 \u0634\u0647\u06cc\u062f \u0633\u0644\u0637\u0627\u0646\u06cc) \u2013 \u0639\u0638\u06cc\u0645\u06cc\u0647 \u2013 \u0628\u0644\u0648\u0627\u0631 \u0645\u0648\u0630\u0646 \u2013 \u0628\u0627\u063a\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646'''\n| 14km (9mi)\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | 12\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#FFFFFF; background-color:#ff0000\" | '''[[Tehran Metro Line 4|{{color|black|4}}]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" |'''\u0628\u0627\u063a\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 \u2013 \u0641\u0631\u0648\u062f\u06af\u0627\u0647 \u067e\u06cc\u0627\u0645'''\n| 18km (11.1mi)\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | 19\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#FFFFFF; background-color:#e2bae2\" | '''[[Tehran Metro Line 5|{{color|blacl|5}}]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" |'''\u0628\u0644\u0648\u0627\u0631 \u0634\u0647\u06cc\u062f \u0645\u0648\u0630\u0646 (\u062f\u0627\u0646\u0634\u06af\u0627\u0647 \u0622\u0632\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u06cc) \u2013 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0634\u0647\u0631'''\n| 12km (7.5mi)\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | 10\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#FFFFFF; background-color:#FF5599\" | '''[[Tehran Metro Line 6|{{color|black|6}}]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" |'''\u0628\u0644\u0648\u0627\u0631 \u062a\u0631\u0628\u06cc\u062a \u0645\u0631\u0628\u06cc \u2013 \u0645\u06cc\u062f\u0627\u0646 \u0634\u0647\u06cc\u062f \u0633\u0644\u0637\u0627\u0646\u06cc'''\n| 9km(6mi)\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | 8\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\" | '''Total:'''\n|'''97km (60mi)'''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | 76\n|}\n\n=== Road ===\nThe highway system of Karaj includes Tehran\u2013Karaj Highway, Karaj Special Road, and the old road of Karaj (Fath Highway). [[Bakeri Expressway|B\u0101keri Expressway]] is one of the main north-to-south routes in west Tehran, which is connected to the Tehran\u2013Karaj Highway.<ref>[http://en.tehran.ir/default.aspx?tabid=77&ArticleId=1562 Main Bridges on Tehran-Karaj Highway Commissioned]</ref> Tehran\u2013Karaj Highway is one of the busiest sections in Iran with [[AADT]] of 217084.<ref>[http://www.tinn.ir/vdcft0dyjw6dj0a.igiw.html \u062a\u0631\u062f\u062f \u0628\u06cc\u0634 \u0627\u0632 \u06cc\u06a9 \u0645\u06cc\u0644\u06cc\u0648\u0646 \u062e\u0648\u062f\u0631\u0648 \u0627\u0632 \u0622\u0632\u0627\u062f\u0631\u0627\u0647 \u062a\u0647\u0631\u0627\u0646 -\u06a9\u0631\u062c] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130812083805/http://tinn.ir/vdcft0dyjw6dj0a.igiw.html |date=2013-08-12}}</ref> Karaj\u2013[[Qazvin]] has an AADT of 79606.\n\nThe aerial transport of Karaj is served by the [[Payam International Airport]], which was established in 1990, and was officially opened in 1997.\n\n{{wide image|Karaj Chalus Road Cross the River LD - panoramio.jpg|1200px|A view of the Karaj-Chalous Road ([[Road 59 (Iran)|Road 59]]) and the Karaj River}}\n\n=== Bus ===\nCurrently, the total number of buses in Karaj and the suburbs are 1,600 units. More than 80 lines serve citizens.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fa.wikivoyage.org/wiki/%DA%A9%D8%B1%D8%AC|title=\u06a9\u0631\u062c - \u0648\u06cc\u06a9\u06cc\u200c\u0633\u0641\u0631|website=fa.wikivoyage.org|language=fa|access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\nPreparing Alborz Card<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alborzcard.ir/|title=Alborz Card - E-pay for transportation}}</ref> can reduce the cost of travel tickets.\n\n== Economy ==\n[[File:\u0645\u0647\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0648\u062c.jpg|thumb|260px|Mahestan Shopping Center]]\nThe economic base of Karaj is its proximity to [[Tehran]]. It is due to the transportation of products between Tehran and the [[Caspian Sea]]. Chemicals, fertilizers and processed agricultural goods are also produced in the city.\n\nKaraj is a major industrial city, with factories producing sugar, textiles, wire, and alcohol. It has become a major area for middle class migrants from Tehran. This is due to the better environmental and cheaper housing conditions.\n\nZowb \u0100han, the avenue leading to an industrial plant, is located at the south of Ostandar Square. ''Zowb e \u0100han'' or ''Zowb \u0100han'', literally \"steel mill\", was a contract between the [[Pahlavi dynasty|Pahlavi]] government and a consortium from [[Nazi Germany]]. The establishment of the factory ''Zowb \u0100han e Karaj'' was halted by the beginning of the [[Second World War]], and it was never launched.\n\n\u0160ahrak e Jah\u0101n\u0161ahr was the first modern private industrial and housing complex of Karaj, built in the 1960s. The factories ''Jah\u0101n \u010cit'' (textile factory), ''Rowqan Nab\u0101ti e Jah\u0101n'' (oil factory), and ''\u010c\u0101y e Jah\u0101n'' (tea factory), were established at the complex. It is one of the largest industrial zones of the nation, with a 20% share of the national GDP <small>[citation?]</small>.\n\nThe [[special economic zone]] of Payam, with an area about 3600 hectares within the territory of [[Payam International Airport]], was established in Karaj for development of air cargo and postal transportation, cold store, and packing services, as well as perishable and time sensitive exports. It is the only SEZ in the region with the privilege of its own [[Payam Air|airline]].\n\n== Education ==\n[[File:Kharazmi University of Karaj 05.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Kharazmi University]] of Karaj]]\n[[File:Abzums medical school in winter.jpg|200px|thumb|Faculty of medicine of [[Alborz university of medical sciences]]]]\nEducational and research centers of the city include:\n* [[Islamic Azad University of Karaj]]\n* [[Kharazmi University]]\n* [[Alborz university of medical sciences]]\n* Faculty of Music of the [[Tehran University of Art]]\n* Faculty of Architecture and Urbanism of the [[Tehran University of Art]]\n* Faculty of Agriculture and Natural Resources of the [[University of Tehran]]\n* University of Environment\n* [[Karaj Payam Noor University|Payam e Noor University of Karaj]]\n* [[Razi Vaccine and Serum Research Institute]] \n* Center for Research in Agriculture and Nuclear Medicine of Karaj\n* Material and Energy Research Center\n\n== Sports ==\n{{see also|Sport in Iran}}\n[[File:Enghelab-Stadium.jpg|thumb|left|200px|[[Enghelab Stadium (Karaj)|Karaj Enqhelab Stadium]]]]\nKaraj was formerly home of the [[Persian Gulf Pro League]] club, [[Saipa F.C.|Saipa]], for several years and this club won its first league championship in this city, however in 2014 the team relocated to Tehran. Currently the only professional football team in city is [[Oxin Alborz F.C.|Oxin Alborz]] that play in the [[Azadegan League]]. The Home stadium of Oxin Alborz F.C. is [[Enghelab Stadium (Karaj)|Enghelab Stadium]] that located in Karaj Enghelab sport complex and has a capacity of 15,000 people.\n\nKaraj also has an international tennis complex which is used to training and tournaments.\n\nOne of the international ski resorts of Iran The, [[Dizin|Dizin ski resort]], is located a few kilometers north-east of the city, in the [[Alborz]]. In Dizin, along with skiing facilities, there are tennis courtyards, a slope for skiing on turf, some altitudes for mountain climbing and walking as well as riding and some routes for cycling.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.itto.org/tourismattractions/?sight=1013&name=Dizin+Ski+Slope |title=ITTO: Dizin Ski Slope |access-date=2010-12-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307133009/http://www.itto.org/tourismattractions/?sight=1013&name=Dizin+Ski+Slope |archive-date=2012-03-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n[[File:Ali Karimi of Iran wears symbolic green wrist bands before the 2010 FIFA World Cup Asian Qualifiers match between Iran and South Korea at Seoul World Cup Stadium.jpg|thumb|170px|Ali Karimi]]\n[[File:Shadi-Amin-IWSF-2013.jpg|thumb|170px|Shadi Amin]]\n[[File:Mehran Rajabi - 2006.JPG|thumb|170px|Mehran Rajabi]]\n[[File:Taekwondo_at_the_2016_Summer_Olympics_women_Kimia_Alizadeh.jpg|thumb|170px|Kimia Alizadeh]]{{See also|Category:People from Karaj}}\n\n=== Academia and scholars ===\n\n* [[Saied Reza Ameli]] (b. 1961), a scholar of communication\n* Seyed Mahdi Alavi (b. 2003), The youngest genius of mathematics and robotics, the smallest recoup teacher at Sharif University of Technology\n\n=== Actors ===\n\n* [[Mehran Rajabi]] (b. 1962), actor\n\n=== Politicians and political activists ===\n\n*[[Fatemeh Ajorlou]] (b. 1966), politician\n*[[Shadi Amin]], political activist, researcher\n*[[Mahmoud Bahmani]] (b. 1947), politician\n\n=== Writers ===\n\n* [[Hossein Sanapour]] (b. 1960), writer\n* [[Saeed Kamali Dehghan]] (b. 1985), journalist\n* [[Fateme Ekhtesari]] (b. 1986), poet\n\n=== Athletes ===\n*[[Ahmad Sanjari]] (b. 1960), football coach\n*[[Farshad Falahatzadeh]] (b. 1967), football player\n*[[Mojtaba Taghavi]] (b. 1968), football player\n*[[Leila Esfandyari]] (1970\u20132011), mountain climber\n*[[Alireza Heidari]] (b. 1976), Olympic wrestler\n*[[Ali Karimi]] (b. 1978), football player\n*[[Ebrahim Sadeghi]] (b. 1979), football player\n*[[Mohammad Nosrati]] (b. 1981), football player\n*[[Rouhollah Dadashi]] (1982\u20132011), powerlifter\n*[[Ebrahim Masoudi]] (b. 1982), futsal player\n*[[Mehdi Mahdavi]] (b. 1984), volleyball player\n*[[Ali Mohammadi (wrestler)|Ali Mohammadi]] (b. 1984), wrestler\n*[[Afshin Kazemi]] (b. 1986), futsal player\n*[[Amin Manouchehri]] (b. 1986), football player\n*[[Reza Mohammadi]] (b. 1986), football player\n*[[Ali Kiaei]] (b. 1987), futsal player\n*[[Mehrdad Pooladi]] (b. 1987), football player\n*[[Milad Farahani]] (b. 1988), football player\n*[[Kimia Alizade]] (b. 1998), Iranian first female and youngest Olympic medalist\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Iran}}\n* [[Morvarid Palace|Morv\u0101rid Palace]]\n* [[Mehrshahr|Mehr\u0161ahr]]\n* [[Amir Kabir Dam]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikivoyage|Karaj}}\n{{Commons category|Karaj}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071212161420/http://karajiha.ir/ Karaj city portal] {{in lang|fa}}<!--Farsi-->\n* [http://www.karaj.co/ About Karaj city] {{in lang|fa}}<!--Farsi-->\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120603175752/http://4karaj.com/ Karaj News & Information] {{in lang|fa}}<!--Farsi-->\n* [http://www.tebyan.net/index.aspx?pid=100017 The city of Karaj]\n* [http://www.itto.org/city/?cityid=5 Iran Tourism & Touring Organization]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120607062612/http://www.karaj24.com/ Karaj Magazine] {{in lang|fa}}<!--Farsi-->\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120426041701/http://karaji.net/%D8%A7%D8%B7%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AA-%DA%A9%D8%B1%D8%AC/%D9%BE%D9%8A%D8%B4%D9%8A%D9%86%D9%87-%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%AE%D9%8A-%DA%A9%D8%B1%D8%AC/317 Karaj Background History] {{in lang|fa}}<!--Farsi-->\n\n{{Alborz Province}}\n{{Karaj County}}\n{{Provincial capitals of Iran}}\n{{Largest cities of Iran}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Karaj County]]\n[[Category:Karaj| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Alborz Province]]\n[[Category:Iranian provincial capitals]]\n", "text_old": "{{other places}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name                   = Karaj\n| native_name                     = \u06a9\u0631\u062c\n| native_name_lang                = fa\n| settlement_type                 = City\n| image_skyline                   = \u06a9\u0631\u062c.jpg\n| image_size                      = 300px\n| image_caption                   = \n| image_seal                      = Karaj government logo.svg\n| mapsize                         = 150px\n| pushpin_map                     = Iran\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|35|50|08|N|51|00|37|E|region:IR|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name                = {{IRN}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Provinces of Iran|Province]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[Counties of Iran|County]]\n| subdivision_type3               = [[Bakhsh]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Alborz Province|Alborz]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Karaj County|Karaj]]\n| subdivision_name3               = [[Central District (Karaj County)|Central]]\n| established_title               = \n| established_date                = \n| leader_title                    = Mayor\n| leader_name                     = Ali kamalizade\n| leader_title1                   = City Council Chairman\n| leader_name1                    = abas zare\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_total_km2                  = 162\n| elevation_m                     = 1312\n| population_urban                = 1,592,492 <ref>https://www.amar.org.ir/english</ref>\n| population_metro                = 1,973,470\n| population_as_of                = 2016 Census\n| population_est                  = \n| population_est_as_of            = \n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_blank1_title         = Population Rank in Iran\n| population_blank1               = [[List of Iran cities by population|4th]]\n| area_code                       = 026\n| blank_name                      = [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|Climate]]\n| blank_info                      = [[Semi-arid climate#Cold semi-arid climates|BSk]]\n| website                         = [https://karaj.ir/ karaj.ir]\n| footnotes                       = \n| timezone                        = [[Iran Standard Time|IRST]]\n| utc_offset                      = +3:30\n| timezone_DST                    = [[Iran Daylight Time|IRDT]]\n| utc_offset_DST                  = +4:30\n}}\n'''Karaj''' ({{lang-fa|\u06a9\u0631\u062c}}, {{IPA-fa|k\u00e6\u02c8\u027e\u00e6d\u0292|pron|Karaj.ogg}}) is the capital of [[Alborz Province]], [[Iran]], and effectively a suburb of [[Tehran]]. Although the county hosts a population around 1.97 million, as recorded in the 2016 census, most of the 1,419 sq km county is rugged mountain, the urban area is the fourth-largest in Iran, after [[Tehran]], [[Mashhad]], and [[Isfahan]].<ref>City Population: ''[http://www.citypopulation.de/Iran-MajorCities.html IRAN: Major Cities]''</ref> [[Eshtehard County]] and Fardis County were split off from Karaj county since the previous census.\n\nThe earliest records of Karaj date back to 30th century BC. The city was developed under the rule of the [[Safavid dynasty|Safavid]] and [[Qajar dynasty|Qajar dynasties]], and is home to historical buildings and memorials from those eras. Until the second half of the 20th century, it used to be known mainly as a summer resort. Today, it is a major industrial city, with factories producing sugar, textiles, wire, and alcohol.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Shah-Abbasi Caravansaray, Karaj.jpg|thumb|230px|left|Shah-Abbasi [[Caravansary]]]]\n\nKaraj has been hosting communities since 3000 years BC.<ref>L. van den Berghe, ''La n\u00e9cropole de Kh\u016brv\u012bn'', Istanbul, Nederlands Historisch-Archaeologisch Instituut in het Nabije Oosten, 1964.</ref><ref name=\"iranica\">[http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/karaj-city-modern-city Karaj i. Modern City]</ref> The [[Khurvin|Khurvin region]] of Karaj has been inhabited since the [[Bronze Age]], and the [[Hemmatabad, Alborz|Kelak region]] on the left bank of [[Karaj River]] since the [[Iron Age]].\n\nThe stone built ''Takht-e Rostam'', located on a mount in the west of [[Shahriar County]], was built in the [[Parthia]]n era as a [[Zoroastrian]] [[fire temple]].\n\nUntil the late 20th century, the city was mainly crossed into by a stone bridge built in the [[Safavid era]]. The stone built ''Shah-Abbasi [[Caravansary]]'', located at the southeast of Towhid Square, was built in the same era, under the rule of [[Shah Ismail|\u0160\u0101h Esm\u0101il]].<ref name=\"iranica\"/>\n\n[[File:Pearl Palace -Kakh e Morvarid- Karaj Iran.jpg|thumb|220px|left|[[Morvarid Palace]] in Karaj]]\nIn the 1810s, the Palace of Soleymaniye, which included four towers surrounded by gardens and walls, was built as a summer resort by the order of Shahzaden Soleyman (Soleyman Mirza), an old prince governor of [[Kermanshah|Kerm\u0101n\u0161\u0101h]].<ref name=\"iranica\"/> Granted in the [[Pahlavi era]] by [[Reza Shah Pahlavi|Rez\u0101 \u0160\u0101h Pahlavi]], it is now housing the Faculty of Agriculture of the [[University of Tehran]].\n\nThe [[Morvarid Palace|Morv\u0101rid Palace]] was constructed in nearby [[Mehrshahr|Mehr\u0161ahr]] district, during the [[Pahlavi era]]. It was designed by the ''[[Frank Lloyd Wright]] Foundation'' ([[Taliesin Associated Architects]]) on instructions from [[Shams Pahlavi]], elder sister of [[Mohammad Reza Pahlavi]]. Majority of the structure is now controlled by the [[Basij|Basij Organization]], and some sections of it are open to public under the operation of [[Cultural Heritage Organization of Iran]].\n\nOther historical sites of the city include the Mausoleum of \u0160\u0101hz\u0101de Soleym\u0101n, [[Imamzadeh|Em\u0101mz\u0101de]] Rahm\u0101n, Em\u0101mz\u0101de Zeyd, and [[Palangabad District|Palang \u0100b\u0101d]] e [[Eshtehard County|E\u0161teh\u0101rd]].<ref>[http://www.itto.org/city/?cityid=5 Itto: Karaj]</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\n[[File:Mehrshahr view.jpg|250px|thumb|right|[[Mehrshahr|Mehr\u0161ahr]], Karaj]]\nKaraj is situated {{convert|20|km|mi}} west of [[Tehran]], at the foothills of the [[Alborz]] mountains.\n\nBuilt on a wide plain with some gentle hills, the city is located north of the agricultural plain of \u0160ahri\u0101r and east of the plains of S\u0101voj Bol\u0101q and Ha\u0161tgerd.\n\n=== Regions ===\n[[file:karaj Taleghani.jpg|250px|left|thumb|A view of Taleghani boulevard towers]]\nThe downtown of Karaj is usually referred to Karaj Square, located hundred of meters to the west of Karaj River and the old Karaj Bridge. The villages Hes\u0101rak, Gowhar Da\u0161t, and \u0160ahrak e Azimie are located in the northern Greater Karaj.\nMehr\u0161ahr, an abortive residential luxury resort, and \u0160ahrak e Fardis, a popular modern quarter close to the industrial facilities,<ref>''[http://iranian.com/Kasraie/2004/June/Design/index.html Frank Lloyd Wright Foundation's deteriorating masterpiece in Iran]'', Nima Kasraie - June 4, 2004</ref> were designed by the ''Frank Lloyd Wright Foundation'' in the late 1960s.\n\nMe\u0161kin Da\u0161t, a large agricultural area between Mehr\u0161ahr and Fardis, lies outside the municipal limits of Karaj.\n\nThe following table includes the major districts of the city:\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:80%; text-align:center\"\n|-\n|[[Gohardasht|Gouhar Da\u015dt]]\n|[[Mehrshahr|Mehr\u015dahr]]\n|[[Kianmehr|Ki\u0101nmehr]]\n|[[Karaj no|Karaj e Now]]\n|[[Hesarak, Karaj|Hes\u0101rak]]\n|[[Derakhti|Deraxti]]\n|Azimie\n|Ouj\n|\u015c\u0101hin Vill\u0101\n|Bony\u0101d\n|B\u0101qest\u0101n\n|[[Doulatabad, Alborz|Doulat \u0100b\u0101d]]\n|-\n|[[Garmdarreh|Garm Darre]]\n|\u015cahrake Jah\u0101n\u015dahr\n|Mesb\u0101h\n|Mehr Vill\u0101\n|Dehq\u0101n Vill\u0101\n|[[Mahdasht|M\u0101hda\u015dt]]\n|\u015cahrake Banaf\u015de\n|[[Fardis]]\n|Vahdat\n|Kal\u0101k o Hes\u0101r\n|Est\u0101m \u0100b\u0101d\n|Gol\u015dahr\n|-\n|Gol\u015dahr Vill\u0101\n|Zib\u0101 Da\u015dt\n|Zoube \u0100han\n|S\u0101s\u0101ni\n|Hom\u0101yun Vill\u0101\n|[[Mohamadshahr|Mehr\u0101n\u015dahr]]\n|[[Mehdiabad, Savojbolagh|Mehdi \u0100b\u0101d]]\n|\u015cahrake X\u0101tam\n|Mi\u0101n J\u0101dde\n|Heydar \u0100b\u0101d\n|S\u0101woj Bol\u0101q\n|Bah\u0101rest\u0101n\n|}\n\nOpen space recreational areas of Karaj include Ir\u0101nzamin Park, P\u0101rk e X\u0101nv\u0101de, Tennis Park, P\u0101rk e M\u0101dar, T\u0101leq\u0101n Gardens, Kord\u0101n Gardens, Jah\u0101n\u0161ahr Gardens, Pardis e Golh\u0101, and the Tulip Garden of Ga\u010ds\u0101r.\n\n=== Climate ===\nThe climate of Karaj is a bit cooler than Tehran's, and it receives 260&nbsp;mm of rain annually (and like Tehran, the precipitation pattern is similar to those of Mediterranean climates). The [[K\u00f6ppen-Geiger climate classification system]] classifies the city's climate as [[cold semi-arid climate|cold semi-arid]] (BSk).<ref name=\"Climate-Data.org\">{{cite web|title=Climate: Karaj - Climate graph, Temperature graph, Climate table|url=http://en.climate-data.org/location/2098/|publisher=Climate-Data.org|accessdate=9 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n{{Weather box\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|location = Karaj (1985\u20132010)\n|Jan record high C = 18.2\n|Feb record high C = 19.8\n|Mar record high C = 27.4\n|Apr record high C = 33.0\n|May record high C = 34.6\n|Jun record high C = 39.2\n|Jul record high C = 42.0\n|Aug record high C = 40.2\n|Sep record high C = 37.2\n|Oct record high C = 31.8\n|Nov record high C = 25.0\n|Dec record high C = 20.0\